<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Flask on Aurora</title><link>https://notes.yoooo.fun/tags/flask/</link><description>Recent content in Flask on Aurora</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Wed, 11 Nov 2020 16:31:07 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://notes.yoooo.fun/tags/flask/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Create a middleware in Flask</title><link>https://notes.yoooo.fun/posts/middleware-in-flask/</link><pubDate>Fri, 18 Sep 2020 11:14:26 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://notes.yoooo.fun/posts/middleware-in-flask/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="middleware-in-flask"&gt;Middleware in Flask
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;How to implement middleware in Flask, just like in Django?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In Flask, we can implement it by &lt;strong&gt;WSGI middleware&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="wsgi-middleware"&gt;WSGI Middleware
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;A WSGI middleware component is a Python callable that is itself a WSGI application, but may handle requests by delegating to other WSGI applications.
These applications can themselves be WSGI middleware components.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A middleware component can perform such functions as:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing a request to different application objects based on the target URL, after changing the environment variables accordingly.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Allowing multiple applications or frameworks to run side-by-side in the same process&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Load balancing and remote processing, by forwarding requests and responses over a network&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Performing content post-processing, such as applying XSLT stylesheets&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
